durch eine auf die lateinamerikanische Geschichte und Gegenwart bezogene Reflexion von Schlüsselbegriffen des Marxismus bestimmt. So gewinnt sein Schreiben vor dem Horizont der globalen Verwerfungen des 20. Jahrhunderts eine Kontur, deren Linien auch auf die Konflikte des 21. Jahrhunderts verweisen.  aThis study interprets the writings of Mexican Nobel Prize laureate Octavio Paz as an open dialectics staged in poetic form and offers new perspectives on his works. By highlighting Paz’s convergence with the Frankfurt School, it offers a key to his thinking about history. Tracing the outlines of his writing against the horizon of the global fault lines of the 20th century, this book makes it relevant to the conflicts of the 21st century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 4aDichtung und Gesellschaft. 4aFrankfurter Schule. 4aIdeengeschichte. 4aPaz, Octavio. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / Hispanic American.2bisacsh  aCritical theory.  aFrankfurt School.  aMexican intellectual history.  apoetry and society.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2019z978311071956708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Studies 2019z9783110606348oZDB-23-DKU0 cEPUBz97831106314490 cprintz978311063120340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311063398640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110633986423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9783110633986.jpg  a978-3-11-071956-7  DG Plus eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DGGb2019  aZDB-23-DKUb2019